            <p>The arrival of Buddhism in the 3rd century BC, brought by Arahat Mahinda (son of Emperor Ashoka of India), transformed Anuradhapura into a major center of Buddhist learning and worship. Kings like Dutugemunu, Valagamba, and Mahasena contributed to the city's architectural brilliance by constructing massive stupas, reservoirs, and monastic complexes.</p>
            <p>Despite its prosperity, Anuradhapura faced repeated invasions from South Indian kingdoms, leading to its decline in the 11th century AD, when the capital was moved to Polonnaruwa. However, it remained a sacred pilgrimage site and continues to be revered by Buddhists worldwide.</p>
